A Realist Analysis of Nonprofit Tax Filing Services

Kevin Schachter
Graduate Student, University of Manitoba
Information Manager, SEED Winnipeg

This research received generous financial support from the Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council of Canada through The Joseph-Armand Bombardier Canada Graduate Scholarship–Master’s Program and The Manitoba Research Alliance grant, “Partnering for Change – Community-based solutions for Aboriginal and inner-city poverty.”

- Based upon thesis research on the nonprofit sector's role in facilitating access to government benefits by low-income community members
- Semi-structured key person interviews in Winnipeg
- Document analysis
- Literature review

Tax Filing through the “Shadow State”

  • Devolution of CVITP coordination to community organizations
  • The creation of a nonprofit “tax empire” to effectively deliver tax filing services

Source: Jennifer Wolch, “The Shadow State: Transformations in the Voluntary Sector,” in The Power of Geography: How Territory Shapes Social Life, ed. Jennifer R. Wolch and Michael J. Dear (Boston: Unwin Hyman, 1989), 197–221.

  • “a para-state apparatus with collective service responsibilities previously shouldered by the public sector, administered outside democratic politics, but yet controlled in both formal and informal ways by the state.” (Wolch 1989:201)
  • Reduces the status of income benefits from entitlement to aid

Opportunities

  • Increased availability of tax filing services
  • …delivered by trusted organizations
  • …in culturally relevant ways
  • …adapted to local conditions and needs

Constraints

  • “Philanthropic insufficiency”
  • “Philanthropic particularism”
  • “Philanthropic amateurism”

Source: Lester M. Salamon, “Of Market Failure, Voluntary Failure, and Third-Party Government: Toward a Theory of Government-Nonprofit Relations in the Modern Welfare State,” Nonprofit and Voluntary Sector Quarterly 16, no. 1–2 (1987)

  • Insufficiency
    • Nonprofit sector has marginal reach and capacity compared to the state
    • Problems with securing funding without recourse to taxation
    • Via government contracts, charitable funding, business activities, user fees
    • Needing to turn community members away due to insufficient capacity
    • Long lineups for services
    • Community members contend with long lineups and call queues to access CVITP support
    • Community need outstrips nonprofit program delivery capacity
  • Particularism
    • can cater services to reach specific demographics and geographic areas
    • can choose whether or not to be publicly listed by CRA
    • can file returns for specific tax years only
    • No universal mandate
  • Amateurism
    • CVITP volunteers can only file returns for people with simple income tax situations
    • Some of the most vulnerable community members may be ineligible for CVITP
      • Surviving spouses / common-law partners of deceased persons
      • Precariously self-employed individuals
    • Double-edged sword – make sure that volunteers are qualified and aren’t burdened with too much responsibility; but limits access for people whose income situations don’t qualify.
    • I suggest that these limitations on eligibility for CVITP reflect an appraisal of the skillset of volunteers, the amount of responsibility they take on, and that CRA takes on in training them.
    • “Agencies stressing volunteer effort and limited by dependence on contributions from providing adequate wages [may be] in a poor position to attract such professional personnel.” (Salamon 1987, 42)
